name: JSONRPCMessage
comment: Refers to any valid JSON-RPC object that can be decoded off the wire, or encoded to be sent.
nodeText:
export type JSONRPCMessage =
  | JSONRPCRequest
  | JSONRPCNotification
  | JSONRPCBatchRequest
  | JSONRPCResponse
  | JSONRPCError
  | JSONRPCBatchResponse;

astStructure.name: JSONRPCMessage
astStructure.type:
| JSONRPCRequest
  | JSONRPCNotification
  | JSONRPCBatchRequest
  | JSONRPCResponse
  | JSONRPCError
  | JSONRPCBatchResponse

name: JSONRPCBatchRequest
comment: A JSON-RPC batch request, as described in https://www.jsonrpc.org/specification#batch.
nodeText: export type JSONRPCBatchRequest = (JSONRPCRequest | JSONRPCNotification)[];

name: JSONRPCBatchResponse
comment: A JSON-RPC batch response, as described in https://www.jsonrpc.org/specification#batch.
nodeText: export type JSONRPCBatchResponse = (JSONRPCResponse | JSONRPCError)[];

name: ProgressToken
comment: A progress token, used to associate progress notifications with the original request.
nodeText: export type ProgressToken = string | number;

name: Cursor
comment: An opaque token used to represent a cursor for pagination.
nodeText: export type Cursor = string;

name: Request

members.name: params
_meta
progressToken
members.comment: If specified, the caller is requesting out-of-band progress notifications for this request (as represented by notifications/progress). The value of this parameter is an opaque token that will be attached to any subsequent notifications. The receiver is not obligated to provide these notifications.

name: Notification

members.name: params
_meta
members.comment: This parameter name is reserved by MCP to allow clients and servers to attach additional metadata to their notifications.

name: Result

members.name: _meta
members.comment: This result property is reserved by the protocol to allow clients and servers to attach additional metadata to their responses.

name: RequestId
comment: A uniquely identifying ID for a request in JSON-RPC.
nodeText: export type RequestId = string | number;

name: JSONRPCRequest
comment: A request that expects a response.

name: JSONRPCNotification
comment: A notification which does not expect a response.

name: JSONRPCResponse
comment: A successful (non-error) response to a request.

name: JSONRPCError
comment: A response to a request that indicates an error occurred.

members.name: error
code
members.comment: The error type that occurred.

members.name: message
members.comment: A short description of the error. The message SHOULD be limited to a concise single sentence.

members.name: data
members.comment: Additional information about the error. The value of this member is defined by the sender (e.g. detailed error information, nested errors etc.).

name: EmptyResult
comment: A response that indicates success but carries no data.
nodeText: export type EmptyResult = Result;

name: CancelledNotification
comment:
This notification can be sent by either side to indicate that it is cancelling a previously-issued request.

The request SHOULD still be in-flight, but due to communication latency, it is always possible that this notification MAY arrive after the request has already finished.

This notification indicates that the result will be unused, so any associated processing SHOULD cease.

A client MUST NOT attempt to cancel its `initialize` request.

members.name: params
requestId
members.comment:
The ID of the request to cancel.

This MUST correspond to the ID of a request previously issued in the same direction.

members.name: reason
members.comment: An optional string describing the reason for the cancellation. This MAY be logged or presented to the user.

name: InitializeRequest
comment: This request is sent from the client to the server when it first connects, asking it to begin initialization.

members.name: params
protocolVersion
members.comment: The latest version of the Model Context Protocol that the client supports. The client MAY decide to support older versions as well.

name: InitializeResult
comment: After receiving an initialize request from the client, the server sends this response.

members.name: protocolVersion
members.comment: The version of the Model Context Protocol that the server wants to use. This may not match the version that the client requested. If the client cannot support this version, it MUST disconnect.

members.name: instructions
members.comment:
Instructions describing how to use the server and its features.

This can be used by clients to improve the LLM's understanding of available tools, resources, etc. It can be thought of like a "hint" to the model. For example, this information MAY be added to the system prompt.

name: InitializedNotification
comment: This notification is sent from the client to the server after initialization has finished.

name: ClientCapabilities
comment: Capabilities a client may support. Known capabilities are defined here, in this schema, but this is not a closed set: any client can define its own, additional capabilities.

members.name: experimental
members.comment: Experimental, non-standard capabilities that the client supports.

members.name: roots
members.comment: Present if the client supports listing roots.

members.name: listChanged
members.comment: Whether the client supports notifications for changes to the roots list.

members.name: sampling
members.comment: Present if the client supports sampling from an LLM.

name: ServerCapabilities
comment: Capabilities that a server may support. Known capabilities are defined here, in this schema, but this is not a closed set: any server can define its own, additional capabilities.

members.name: experimental
members.comment: Experimental, non-standard capabilities that the server supports.

members.name: logging
members.comment: Present if the server supports sending log messages to the client.

members.name: completions
members.comment: Present if the server supports argument autocompletion suggestions.

members.name: prompts
members.comment: Present if the server offers any prompt templates.

members.name: listChanged
members.comment: Whether this server supports notifications for changes to the prompt list.

members.name: resources
members.comment: Present if the server offers any resources to read.

members.name: subscribe
members.comment: Whether this server supports subscribing to resource updates.

members.name: listChanged
members.comment: Whether this server supports notifications for changes to the resource list.

members.name: tools
members.comment: Present if the server offers any tools to call.

members.name: listChanged
members.comment: Whether this server supports notifications for changes to the tool list.

name: Implementation
comment: Describes the name and version of an MCP implementation.

name: PingRequest
comment: A ping, issued by either the server or the client, to check that the other party is still alive. The receiver must promptly respond, or else may be disconnected.

name: ProgressNotification
comment: An out-of-band notification used to inform the receiver of a progress update for a long-running request.

members.name: params
progressToken
members.comment: The progress token which was given in the initial request, used to associate this notification with the request that is proceeding.

members.name: progress
members.comment: The progress thus far. This should increase every time progress is made, even if the total is unknown.

members.name: total
members.comment: Total number of items to process (or total progress required), if known.

members.name: message
members.comment: An optional message describing the current progress.

name: PaginatedRequest

members.name: params
cursor
members.comment:
An opaque token representing the current pagination position.
If provided, the server should return results starting after this cursor.

name: PaginatedResult

members.name: nextCursor
members.comment:
An opaque token representing the pagination position after the last returned result.
If present, there may be more results available.

name: ListResourcesRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request a list of resources the server has.

name: ListResourcesResult
comment: The server's response to a resources/list request from the client.

name: ListResourceTemplatesRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request a list of resource templates the server has.

name: ListResourceTemplatesResult
comment: The server's response to a resources/templates/list request from the client.

name: ReadResourceRequest
comment: Sent from the client to the server, to read a specific resource URI.

members.name: params
uri
members.comment: The URI of the resource to read. The URI can use any protocol; it is up to the server how to interpret it.

name: ReadResourceResult
comment: The server's response to a resources/read request from the client.

name: ResourceListChangedNotification
comment: An optional notification from the server to the client, informing it that the list of resources it can read from has changed. This may be issued by servers without any previous subscription from the client.

name: SubscribeRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request resources/updated notifications from the server whenever a particular resource changes.

members.name: params
uri
members.comment: The URI of the resource to subscribe to. The URI can use any protocol; it is up to the server how to interpret it.

name: UnsubscribeRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request cancellation of resources/updated notifications from the server. This should follow a previous resources/subscribe request.

members.name: params
uri
members.comment: The URI of the resource to unsubscribe from.

name: ResourceUpdatedNotification
comment: A notification from the server to the client, informing it that a resource has changed and may need to be read again. This should only be sent if the client previously sent a resources/subscribe request.

members.name: params
uri
members.comment: The URI of the resource that has been updated. This might be a sub-resource of the one that the client actually subscribed to.

name: Resource
comment: A known resource that the server is capable of reading.

members.name: uri
members.comment: The URI of this resource.

members.name: name
members.comment:
A human-readable name for this resource.

This can be used by clients to populate UI elements.

members.name: description
members.comment:
A description of what this resource represents.

This can be used by clients to improve the LLM's understanding of available resources. It can be thought of like a "hint" to the model.

members.name: mimeType
members.comment: The MIME type of this resource, if known.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: ResourceTemplate
comment: A template description for resources available on the server.

members.name: uriTemplate
members.comment: A URI template (according to RFC 6570) that can be used to construct resource URIs.

members.name: name
members.comment:
A human-readable name for the type of resource this template refers to.

This can be used by clients to populate UI elements.

members.name: description
members.comment:
A description of what this template is for.

This can be used by clients to improve the LLM's understanding of available resources. It can be thought of like a "hint" to the model.

members.name: mimeType
members.comment: The MIME type for all resources that match this template. This should only be included if all resources matching this template have the same type.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: ResourceContents
comment: The contents of a specific resource or sub-resource.

members.name: uri
members.comment: The URI of this resource.

members.name: mimeType
members.comment: The MIME type of this resource, if known.

name: TextResourceContents

members.name: text
members.comment: The text of the item. This must only be set if the item can actually be represented as text (not binary data).

name: BlobResourceContents

members.name: blob
members.comment: A base64-encoded string representing the binary data of the item.

name: ListPromptsRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request a list of prompts and prompt templates the server has.

name: ListPromptsResult
comment: The server's response to a prompts/list request from the client.

name: GetPromptRequest
comment: Used by the client to get a prompt provided by the server.

members.name: params
name
members.comment: The name of the prompt or prompt template.

members.name: arguments
members.comment: Arguments to use for templating the prompt.

name: GetPromptResult
comment: The server's response to a prompts/get request from the client.

members.name: description
members.comment: An optional description for the prompt.

name: Prompt
comment: A prompt or prompt template that the server offers.

members.name: name
members.comment: The name of the prompt or prompt template.

members.name: description
members.comment: An optional description of what this prompt provides

members.name: arguments
members.comment: A list of arguments to use for templating the prompt.

name: PromptArgument
comment: Describes an argument that a prompt can accept.

members.name: name
members.comment: The name of the argument.

members.name: description
members.comment: A human-readable description of the argument.

members.name: required
members.comment: Whether this argument must be provided.

name: Role
comment: The sender or recipient of messages and data in a conversation.
nodeText: export type Role = "user" | "assistant";

name: PromptMessage
comment:
Describes a message returned as part of a prompt.

This is similar to `SamplingMessage`, but also supports the embedding of
resources from the MCP server.

name: EmbeddedResource
comment:
The contents of a resource, embedded into a prompt or tool call result.

It is up to the client how best to render embedded resources for the benefit
of the LLM and/or the user.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: PromptListChangedNotification
comment: An optional notification from the server to the client, informing it that the list of prompts it offers has changed. This may be issued by servers without any previous subscription from the client.

name: ListToolsRequest
comment: Sent from the client to request a list of tools the server has.

name: ListToolsResult
comment: The server's response to a tools/list request from the client.

name: CallToolResult
comment:
The server's response to a tool call.

Any errors that originate from the tool SHOULD be reported inside the result
object, with `isError` set to true, _not_ as an MCP protocol-level error
response. Otherwise, the LLM would not be able to see that an error occurred
and self-correct.

However, any errors in _finding_ the tool, an error indicating that the
server does not support tool calls, or any other exceptional conditions,
should be reported as an MCP error response.

members.name: isError
members.comment:
Whether the tool call ended in an error.

If not set, this is assumed to be false (the call was successful).

name: CallToolRequest
comment: Used by the client to invoke a tool provided by the server.

name: ToolListChangedNotification
comment: An optional notification from the server to the client, informing it that the list of tools it offers has changed. This may be issued by servers without any previous subscription from the client.

name: ToolAnnotations
comment:
Additional properties describing a Tool to clients.

NOTE: all properties in ToolAnnotations are **hints**.
They are not guaranteed to provide a faithful description of
tool behavior (including descriptive properties like `title`).

Clients should never make tool use decisions based on ToolAnnotations
received from untrusted servers.

members.name: title
members.comment: A human-readable title for the tool.

members.name: readOnlyHint
members.comment:
If true, the tool does not modify its environment.

Default: false

members.name: destructiveHint
members.comment:
If true, the tool may perform destructive updates to its environment.
If false, the tool performs only additive updates.

(This property is meaningful only when `readOnlyHint == false`)

Default: true

members.name: idempotentHint
members.comment:
If true, calling the tool repeatedly with the same arguments
will have no additional effect on the its environment.

(This property is meaningful only when `readOnlyHint == false`)

Default: false

members.name: openWorldHint
members.comment:
If true, this tool may interact with an "open world" of external
entities. If false, the tool's domain of interaction is closed.
For example, the world of a web search tool is open, whereas that
of a memory tool is not.

Default: true

name: Tool
comment: Definition for a tool the client can call.

members.name: name
members.comment: The name of the tool.

members.name: description
members.comment:
A human-readable description of the tool.

This can be used by clients to improve the LLM's understanding of available tools. It can be thought of like a "hint" to the model.

members.name: inputSchema
members.comment: A JSON Schema object defining the expected parameters for the tool.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional additional tool information.

name: SetLevelRequest
comment: A request from the client to the server, to enable or adjust logging.

members.name: params
level
members.comment: The level of logging that the client wants to receive from the server. The server should send all logs at this level and higher (i.e., more severe) to the client as notifications/message.

name: LoggingMessageNotification
comment: Notification of a log message passed from server to client. If no logging/setLevel request has been sent from the client, the server MAY decide which messages to send automatically.

members.name: params
level
members.comment: The severity of this log message.

members.name: logger
members.comment: An optional name of the logger issuing this message.

members.name: data
members.comment: The data to be logged, such as a string message or an object. Any JSON serializable type is allowed here.

name: LoggingLevel
comment:
The severity of a log message.

These map to syslog message severities, as specified in RFC-5424:
https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5424#section-6.2.1
nodeText:
export type LoggingLevel =
  | "debug"
  | "info"
  | "notice"
  | "warning"
  | "error"
  | "critical"
  | "alert"
  | "emergency";

name: CreateMessageRequest
comment: A request from the server to sample an LLM via the client. The client has full discretion over which model to select. The client should also inform the user before beginning sampling, to allow them to inspect the request (human in the loop) and decide whether to approve it.

members.name: params
modelPreferences
members.comment: The server's preferences for which model to select. The client MAY ignore these preferences.

members.name: systemPrompt
members.comment: An optional system prompt the server wants to use for sampling. The client MAY modify or omit this prompt.

members.name: includeContext
members.comment: A request to include context from one or more MCP servers (including the caller), to be attached to the prompt. The client MAY ignore this request.

members.name: maxTokens
members.comment: The maximum number of tokens to sample, as requested by the server. The client MAY choose to sample fewer tokens than requested.

members.name: metadata
members.comment: Optional metadata to pass through to the LLM provider. The format of this metadata is provider-specific.

name: CreateMessageResult
comment: The client's response to a sampling/create_message request from the server. The client should inform the user before returning the sampled message, to allow them to inspect the response (human in the loop) and decide whether to allow the server to see it.

members.name: model
members.comment: The name of the model that generated the message.

members.name: stopReason
members.comment: The reason why sampling stopped, if known.

name: SamplingMessage
comment: Describes a message issued to or received from an LLM API.

name: Annotations
comment: Optional annotations for the client. The client can use annotations to inform how objects are used or displayed

members.name: audience
members.comment:
Describes who the intended customer of this object or data is.

It can include multiple entries to indicate content useful for multiple audiences (e.g., `["user", "assistant"]`).

members.name: priority
members.comment:
Describes how important this data is for operating the server.

A value of 1 means "most important," and indicates that the data is
effectively required, while 0 means "least important," and indicates that
the data is entirely optional.

name: TextContent
comment: Text provided to or from an LLM.

members.name: text
members.comment: The text content of the message.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: ImageContent
comment: An image provided to or from an LLM.

members.name: data
members.comment: The base64-encoded image data.

members.name: mimeType
members.comment: The MIME type of the image. Different providers may support different image types.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: AudioContent
comment: Audio provided to or from an LLM.

members.name: data
members.comment: The base64-encoded audio data.

members.name: mimeType
members.comment: The MIME type of the audio. Different providers may support different audio types.

members.name: annotations
members.comment: Optional annotations for the client.

name: ModelPreferences
comment:
The server's preferences for model selection, requested of the client during sampling.

Because LLMs can vary along multiple dimensions, choosing the "best" model is
rarely straightforward.  Different models excel in different areassome are
faster but less capable, others are more capable but more expensive, and so
on. This interface allows servers to express their priorities across multiple
dimensions to help clients make an appropriate selection for their use case.

These preferences are always advisory. The client MAY ignore them. It is also
up to the client to decide how to interpret these preferences and how to
balance them against other considerations.
nodeText:
export interface ModelPreferences {
  /**
   * Optional hints to use for model selection.
   *
   * If multiple hints are specified, the client MUST evaluate them in order
   * (such that the first match is taken).
   *
   * The client SHOULD prioritize these hints over the numeric priorities, but
   * MAY still use the priorities to select from ambiguous matches.
   */
  hints?: ModelHint[];

  /**
   * How much to prioritize cost when selecting a model. A value of 0 means cost
   * is not important, while a value of 1 means cost is the most important
   * factor.
   *
   * @TJS-type number
   * @minimum 0
   * @maximum 1
   */
  costPriority?: number;

  /**
   * How much to prioritize sampling speed (latency) when selecting a model. A
   * value of 0 means speed is not important, while a value of 1 means speed is
   * the most important factor.
   *
   * @TJS-type number
   * @minimum 0
   * @maximum 1
   */
  speedPriority?: number;

  /**
   * How much to prioritize intelligence and capabilities when selecting a
   * model. A value of 0 means intelligence is not important, while a value of 1
   * means intelligence is the most important factor.
   *
   * @TJS-type number
   * @minimum 0
   * @maximum 1
   */
  intelligencePriority?: number;
}

members.name: hints
members.comment:
Optional hints to use for model selection.

If multiple hints are specified, the client MUST evaluate them in order
(such that the first match is taken).

The client SHOULD prioritize these hints over the numeric priorities, but
MAY still use the priorities to select from ambiguous matches.

members.name: costPriority
members.comment:
How much to prioritize cost when selecting a model. A value of 0 means cost
is not important, while a value of 1 means cost is the most important
factor.

members.name: speedPriority
members.comment:
How much to prioritize sampling speed (latency) when selecting a model. A
value of 0 means speed is not important, while a value of 1 means speed is
the most important factor.

members.name: intelligencePriority
members.comment:
How much to prioritize intelligence and capabilities when selecting a
model. A value of 0 means intelligence is not important, while a value of 1
means intelligence is the most important factor.

name: ModelHint
comment:
Hints to use for model selection.

Keys not declared here are currently left unspecified by the spec and are up
to the client to interpret.
nodeText:
export interface ModelHint {
  /**
   * A hint for a model name.
   *
   * The client SHOULD treat this as a substring of a model name; for example:
   *  - `claude-3-5-sonnet` should match `claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022`
   *  - `sonnet` should match `claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022`, `claude-3-sonnet-20240229`, etc.
   *  - `claude` should match any Claude model
   *
   * The client MAY also map the string to a different provider's model name or a different model family, as long as it fills a similar niche; for example:
   *  - `gemini-1.5-flash` could match `claude-3-haiku-20240307`
   */
  name?: string;
}

members.name: name
members.comment:
A hint for a model name.

The client SHOULD treat this as a substring of a model name; for example:
 - `claude-3-5-sonnet` should match `claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022`
 - `sonnet` should match `claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022`, `claude-3-sonnet-20240229`, etc.
 - `claude` should match any Claude model

The client MAY also map the string to a different provider's model name or a different model family, as long as it fills a similar niche; for example:
 - `gemini-1.5-flash` could match `claude-3-haiku-20240307`

name: CompleteRequest
comment: A request from the client to the server, to ask for completion options.

members.name: params
argument
members.comment: The argument's information

members.name: name
members.comment: The name of the argument

members.name: value
members.comment: The value of the argument to use for completion matching.

name: CompleteResult
comment: The server's response to a completion/complete request

members.name: completion
values
members.comment: An array of completion values. Must not exceed 100 items.

members.name: total
members.comment: The total number of completion options available. This can exceed the number of values actually sent in the response.

members.name: hasMore
members.comment: Indicates whether there are additional completion options beyond those provided in the current response, even if the exact total is unknown.

name: ResourceReference
comment: A reference to a resource or resource template definition.

members.name: uri
members.comment: The URI or URI template of the resource.

name: PromptReference
comment: Identifies a prompt.

members.name: name
members.comment: The name of the prompt or prompt template

name: ListRootsRequest
comment:
Sent from the server to request a list of root URIs from the client. Roots allow
servers to ask for specific directories or files to operate on. A common example
for roots is providing a set of repositories or directories a server should operate
on.

This request is typically used when the server needs to understand the file system
structure or access specific locations that the client has permission to read from.

name: ListRootsResult
comment:
The client's response to a roots/list request from the server.
This result contains an array of Root objects, each representing a root directory
or file that the server can operate on.

name: Root
comment: Represents a root directory or file that the server can operate on.

members.name: uri
members.comment:
The URI identifying the root. This *must* start with file:// for now.
This restriction may be relaxed in future versions of the protocol to allow
other URI schemes.

members.name: name
members.comment:
An optional name for the root. This can be used to provide a human-readable
identifier for the root, which may be useful for display purposes or for
referencing the root in other parts of the application.

name: RootsListChangedNotification
comment:
A notification from the client to the server, informing it that the list of roots has changed.
This notification should be sent whenever the client adds, removes, or modifies any root.
The server should then request an updated list of roots using the ListRootsRequest.

name: ClientRequest
nodeText:
export type ClientRequest =
